Computing CIs: an example with fake data

Repeating the example from the presentation

set.seed(6436)
N<-52 # the size of the sample we will create :nerd:
y <- rnorm(N, 50, 5) # Uses the normal distribution with mean = 50, and standard deviation = 5
fake <- data.frame(y=y)
fake %>%
  ggplot(aes(y)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

To rehearse the key idea, we will calculate a 95 percent confidence interval :D theyâ€™re talking about seeing if our tests will still find the mean is 50 or not!

CI

This implies that the mean is around 51.3

Exercise 1a: Complete the code to calculate the confidence limits

Create a bootstrap estimate of the CI for the mean of the fake data. Start by doing this for 40 bootstrap samples, then increase the number of samples appropriately.

:nerd: I forgot to change up this 40 in the lesson, so have a look at the following histograms of x40 bootstrap samples, then x400 bootstraps, then a crazy big x40,000 samples. Look at the axes, have they changed, or has the widow just moved a bit? How else does this change? Try fiddling with the sample size & see what happens.

set.seed(09971654)
sample_size <-52
boot_var_generator <- function(Nb){
Bootvar<-rep(NA,Nb) # creat an empty sample
for(i in seq_len(Nb)){
  temp.boot<-fake$y[sample(seq_len(N),sample_size,replace=TRUE)]
   Bootvar[i] <- var(temp.boot) 
# this takes a sub-sample from fake$y, gets the variance of it, then repeats for Nb tries
}
Bootvar
}
bs_40 <- boot_var_generator(40)
Bootstrap <- data.frame(var_40=bs_40)
ggplot(Bootstrap, aes(x=var_40)) +
geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),binwidth = .5)+
ggtitle("Bootstrapped x40")+
theme_bw()

bs_400 <- boot_var_generator(400)
Bootstrap <- data.frame(var_400=bs_400)
ggplot(Bootstrap, aes(x=var_400)) +
geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),binwidth = .5)+
ggtitle("Bootstrapped x400")+
theme_bw()

Kickstarter Data

This is a large dataset. It may speed things up if you take a random subsample. We will start by selecting only the kickstarter projects with at least one backer!

kickstarter<-kickstarter[kickstarter$backers>0,] 
# this will overwrite the original dataset in R, but not in your original data file.

The following code takes a random sample of 10,000 rows from the data, and then deletes the large dataset. Feel free to reduce the sample size if your computer needs it.

set.seed(7637) # for reproducability!
n_subsample <- 10000 # deliberately much smaller here.
index <- sample(seq_along(kickstarter$ID), n_subsample)
my_kickstarter <- kickstarter[index, ]
rm(kickstarter)

Construct some confidence intervals using the bootstrap approach

To look at some confidence intervals, we will consider the funding goal variable. We will first see how the distribution of funding goals varies by the main category of the funding call.

Create a set of bootstrap samples of your data and then use it to estimate confidence intervals for

  1. Mean of usd_goal_real
  2. Median of usd_goal_real
  3. Variance of usd_goal_real
  4. Mean number of backers by the state of the project.
boot_kicks <- function(Nbootstrap, size=40){
  
MeanBts<-rep(NA,Nbootstrap)
MedianBts<-rep(NA,Nbootstrap)
VarBts<-rep(NA,Nbootstrap)

set.seed(007)
for(i in seq_len(Nbootstrap)){
  usevalues<-sample(seq_along(my_kickstarter$ID),size,replace=TRUE)   
  sample<-my_kickstarter[usevalues,]
  MeanBts[i]<- mean(sample$usd_goal_real) 
  MedianBts[i] <- median(sample$usd_goal_real)
  VarBts[i] <- var(sample$usd_goal_real)
}
Boot_goals <- cbind(data.frame(MeanBts), data.frame(MedianBts), data.frame(VarBts))
Boot_goals
}

Plot a histogram of the values of the bootstrap means

Boot_goals = boot_kicks(50000, 20) #small samples, but lots of them
ggplot(Boot_goals, aes(x=MeanBts)) +
geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),binwidth = 0.02)+
scale_x_log10() +
ggtitle("Bootstrapped Mean Funding Goals")+
theme_bw()

What is the 95% confidence interval of the bootstrap means?

(ciMeans<- quantile(Boot_goals$MeanBts,probs=c(.025,0.975))) # (uncomment out when ready to do the calculation)
##       2.5%      97.5% 
##   6197.058 116829.672
